Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, possibly the most powerful position within the world economy?
An incorrect decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had wide-ranging political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting feeling of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current central bank chief Jerome Powell should be confirmed in office.
It would be proof of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience is needed to lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly these same arguments I have already heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of the economic advisory council of US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was an issue.
They were sufficient to convince Clinton, and the country has paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker a second term in office after he had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed much to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful evaluation and sensitivity to conflicting objectives are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and competitive on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always held clearly different but clearly articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to populist madness).
In my view, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unbridled markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Moreover, we know that traditionally only in tight labor markets are marginalized groups brought into the economy and wage differences reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a trial period for every US central bank chief.
Already now, the US is facing difficult decisions about what to do against inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems arising from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, who have still not regained their pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and thus an increase in unemployment) be worse as a remedy than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the incorrect pricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even stronger and more pervasive mispricing of assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man for the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, even though other central bankers worldwide have already declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not part of the Fed's mandate, yet he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater danger to financial stability than climate change.
Moreover, the Fed is responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's track record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
An acute lack of competition and insufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But any second-year student would have known that during a recession, one must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT has argued, Powell is not particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board, in terms of tightening monetary policy, was marked during the past decade by a series of misjudgments dating back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the concern of the central bank, it is a fact that the bank's policy has important distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early increase in interest rates can choke growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal involving stock trades by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently low awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump having already weakened trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer who decides when certain stock trades would appear improper.
The Fed resembles the US Supreme Court in some respects.
This body is supposed to stand above politics, yet ever since Bush v. Gore, we have known that this is not the case.
Trump made that clear for all those who still had doubts.
Also, the Fed is supposedly independent, yet Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is not the case either by following their party's deregulation agenda.
However, while the central bank board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power traditionally concentrates much more in the hands of the central bank chief than in the hands of the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank chief who decides what comes up for a vote and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is only one example of how critically important it is who sits at the head of the table.
The US needs a central bank that truly commits itself to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Whoever believes that we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation is already going too far lacks insight.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-oriented lawyer like Powell.
What is needed is someone who has deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who fulfill these conditions.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone who has already proven their abilities.
Lael Brainard is already a member of the central bank board, where she has demonstrated her competence and gained the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chair who ensures continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who shares his economic and social program.
